Illumina methylation experiment analysis

Viola Meixian Vuong

Master Degree in Bioinformatics, University of Bologna

The following report describes the analytical pipeline of an Illumina Infinium methylation experiment.
For each of the following steps, codes with their corresponding outputs and, eventually, plots and tables displaying those outputs are also reported.

5 - Perform the following quality checks and provide a brief comment to each step:
5.1 - QCplot
qc <- getQC(MSet.raw)
plotQC(qc)

minfi provides through the functions getQC and plotQC a simple quality control plot. The log median intensity of both conditions, methylated (x-axis) and unmethylated (y-axis), are provided; a dash line that cuts across the plot separates the ‘good’ samples from the ‘bad’ ones (it functions as a sort of cut-off). The plot displays the good quality of our samples, as neither one falls in the ‘bad sample’ region. Therefore, all samples have high median intensity.

5.2 - Check the intensity of negative controls using minfi

controlStripPlot function returns a strip plot of our negative controls. Unfortunately, the color labels are swapped. Nevertheless, we can state here the good quality of the controls. As the background intensity mustn’t be higher than 1000, we can observe that every control lies within 10 (as log2(1000)=10) in the log2 space.

5.3 - Calculate detection pValues; for each sample, how many probes have a detection p-value higher than the threshold assigned to each student?
my_pvalue <- 0.01
detP <- detectionP(RGset)
failed <- detP>my_pvalue

To report in tabular form the number of probes passing and failing the threshold value, the failed matrix was first converted into a dataframe. The matrix was manipulated in such way to obtain a dataframe which rows corresponds to the samples, the columns respectively the number of FALSE and TRUE, with FALSE: probes which are <0.01; TRUE: probes which are >0.01.

failed_df <- t(data.frame(apply(failed, 2, table)))

1. Mean plots
“Mean raw beta values” plot tells us that typeII probes are less sensitive than those of typeI, as its range tends to be more “central”. After the normalization procedure, we can see a shift in terms of peaks, which appear to be aligned to typeI ones.
2. SD plots
The same can be said for the SD plots. The before-normalization behavior of typeII probes is the same depicted in the raw beta values plot, as the peak is shifted towards the center, referring to the less sensitive capacity of typeII probes to detect extreme methylation values. The normalization procedure aligns the peaks to one another.
3. BoxPlots
The normalization procedure of the samples’ beta values lowered significantly the variability. A similar distribution of the beta values across samples can also be observed.

9 - Using the matrix of normalized beta values generated in step 7, identify differentially methylated probes between group WT and group MUT using the function assigned to each student. Note: it can take several minutes; if you encounter any problem you can run the differential methylation analysis only on a subset of probes (for example those on chromosome 1, 18 and 21)

Function assigned: t-test

#Creating an ad hoc function for the t-test
t_test_func <- function(x){
  t_test <- t.test(x ~ SampleSheet$Group)
  return (t_test$p.value)
}
p_value_t_test <- apply(beta_preprocessQuantile, 1, t_test_func)

12 - Produce an heatmap of the top 100 differentially methylated probes.
#Creating a matrix containing our input data for the heatmaps
t_test_df_corrected <- data.frame(t_test_df, p_value_Bon, p_value_BH)
heatmap_data = as.matrix(t_test_df_corrected[1:100, 1:8]) 
#Complete linkage method
colorbar <- c("#377eb8", "#d95f02", "#377eb8", "#377eb8", "#d95f02", "#d95f02", "#377eb8", "#d95f02")
my_col_2 = colorRampPalette(c("#4daf4a", "black", "#e41a1c"))(100)
{heatmap.2(heatmap_data, col = my_col_2, Rowv = T, Colv = T, dendrogram = "both", key = T, ColSideColors = colorbar, density.info = "none", trace = "none", scale = "none", symm = F, main = "Complete linkage")
legend(legend = c("MUT", "WT"), col = c("#d95f02", "#377eb8"), "topright", pch = 15, bty = "n", cex = 0.7)}

#Single linkage method
{heatmap.2(heatmap_data, col = my_col_2, Rowv = T, Colv = T, hclustfun = function(x) hclust(x, method = 'single'), dendrogram = "both", key = T, ColSideColors = colorbar, density.info = "none", trace = "none", scale = "none", symm = F, main = "Single linkage")
legend(legend = c("MUT", "WT"), col = c("#d95f02", "#377eb8"), "topright", pch = 15, bty = "n", cex = 0.7)}

#Average linkage method
{heatmap.2(heatmap_data, col = my_col_2, Rowv = T, Colv = T, hclustfun = function(x) hclust(x, method = 'average'), dendrogram = "both", key = T, ColSideColors = colorbar, density.info = "none", trace = "none", scale = "none", symm = F, main = "Average linkage")
legend(legend = c("MUT", "WT"), col = c("#d95f02", "#377eb8"), "topright", pch = 15, bty = "n", cex = 0.7)}
